<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-155-157 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 765 099</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  May 13 1991 v8 n19 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC helps Bay State start-up companies with subsidies forequipment, services. (Massachusetts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Briggs, George.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (Public relations).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Computer IndustryDonationStart-Up CostsStart-Up FinancingPrice CuttingMassachusettsComputersSupport Services.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DEC helps Bay State start-up companies with subsidies for equipment, servicesandM;BOSTON -- In an effort to help stimulate a sagging Massachusetts economy, DECis offering start-up companies in the state grants of 40 percent to 50percent off list prices for its computer equipment and services.andM;&quot;This idea is to encourage entrepreneurs,&quot; said Kenneth Olsen, DEC'spresident.andM;The grants will be available &quot;to any company that started last year or thisyear,&quot; Olsen said during a press conference at the Massachusetts Statehouse.andM;Under the Entrepreneurial Grant Program, DEC will offer its products andservices with a 40 percent discount to start-up companies.andP;  Personalcomputers and workstations will be offered with a 50 percent grant, accordingto Olsen.andM;The grants will be offered on a one-time basis to fledgling companiesestablished in Massachusetts between May 1, 1990 and June 30, 1992, Olsensaid.andM;DEC hopes to benefit from the grants by encouraging grant recipients tocontinue to buy equipment from DEC.andM;The program helps reduce the risk of taking the entrepreneurial plunge bymaking an essential tool like computers more affordable, Olsen said.andM;DEC started in 1957 with three employees in a woolen mill in Maynard, Mass.andM;It has grown to become the second-largest employer in Massachusetts and the30th largest industrial corporation in the United States, according toFortune magazine.andO;</TEXT></DOC>